Q68. "Exercise name are important"
: Important for what? Adherence, understanding, injury preventation, performance, what?


Q68. "A system that standardizes exercise names would be beneficial"
: Beneficial in what way? In communication between trainers, and users? Sure, maybe. Is this of importance? In general, no. It's like trying to define p-value in 1 sentence - its not needed. With additional sentences and description, the details will become clear. I would, however, think it would be of great(!) importance when describing exercises used in research studies. Still, it does not have to be phrased exactly identical. There is no big deal if one group of researchers describe the exercise as "Seated Plate Loaded Chest Press" and another describes it as "Plate Loaded Seated Chest Press". 

I would prefer details regarding 1) equipment (barbell/dumbbell/cable/...), 2) body position (e.g. standing/sitting/incline/decline, feet together/hip wide, pronated/supinated grip), 3) primary muscle group if possible (e.g. chest), and 4) movement (e.g. press) when describing exercises in a research setting.

Q69: It is impossible to standardise the naming of every lift, due to the vast number of variations available. For every lift you can vary the bench angles and position, bar types, bar positions, body positions, grip width, grip angle, speed, range of motion (including partials, 21s, 1 1/2s, pauses, negatives) etc. You can also add bands, chains etc etc. This is before you consider the more esoteric machines such as the old nautilus machines. Most qualified trainers can identify exercises and most decent gyms have inductions for newbies, so strict naming conventions aren't needed.

Q69:
Whenever possible, I prefer to include the generic name of the training tools (barbell, dumbbell, kettlebell, cable, band), a short description of the body position (lying, standing, split-stance, incline, decline), and the movement pattern (squat, lunge, swing, snatch, bench press, fly, row) in the full name of the exercise.

This helps my new personal training clients to more easily identify the exercise because the exact description is in the name.  For example, ‚ÄúLying EZ Bar Triceps Extensions‚Äù conveys more info to new and remote trainees than the informal name ‚ÄúSkull Crushers‚Äù does.

Eventually, as the trainee gains experience and grows more familiar with each movement, we typically become more lax with any naming conventions.

Q69:
I am a Personal Trainer with many clients. Often I choose exercise names based on the client (with regards their: knowledge, experience, preference, personality & more). 

Often I choose exercise names based on what the CLIENT knows and understands and prefers, not what *I* prefer. 

Eg: I have a client who calls ‚Äúdumbbell standing shoulder press‚Äù, ‚Äútriangle ups‚Äù, because you make a triangle shape with your hands, that goes up above the head. With THIS client I ALSO call it ‚Äúok now let‚Äôs go for some triangle-ups‚Äù, but I do this with NO other client. I want HER to understand and be happy with what she‚Äôs doing, not me or anyone else. 
SHE remembers from the name, to draw a triangle above her head with the dumbbells, this is correct and so helpful to her. So we stick with it.
She also finds it funny that I call it what she calls it. This builds rapport with the client and enhances team spirit and team work. 

Eg2: I have a client who calls ‚Äúlateral raises‚Äù, ‚Äúflappy birds‚Äù as she says she feels like she‚Äôs trying to fly off. 
She dislikes the exercise, but thinks the name is funny. This helps her have less dislike for the exercise AND remember how to perform the technique. So we stick with it. 

Eg3: this also happens with stretching. I do not use the yoga names for stretches unless the client is more advanced or aware of yoga. As I am not trying to complicate things for them with remembering strange names for things. I have a client who says: ‚Äúoh this stretch is like folding your legs like a pretzel‚Äù so now we called it ‚Äúok next let‚Äôs go for the pretzel stretch‚Äù. This que‚Äôs her to remember what position we are going for and what we are trying to do.
Another example, I call one stretch I often do with clients ‚Äúthe diamond stretch‚Äù because your legs are a diamond shape and this makes the position easy to remember and simpler to recognise from the name. That one is MY choice though for simplicity, not a clients.

Most exercise names directly describe what the action or movement and/or equipment is. This is a great thing for understanding.
However if the names are complicated, not direct, OR not preferable to the client. I will opt for simpler version that they themselves prefer.
Some exercises I have several names for them based on what individual clients understand & prefer.
The names are for THEM to understand and perform instructions based on, so THEIR understanding & preference of exercise name is the #1 most important thing. Not what is ‚Äústandard‚Äù or my preference.

With athletes, advanced training populations, or more knowledgable clients I am MORE LIKELY to use correct scientific/advanced names for things.
With people newer to exercise I am more aiming to make things simple and understandable for them, rather than just rigidly stick with science names due to convention.

Hope this helps for my personal perspective & practices.

-

Connor Rhodes
Personal Trainer
Sheffield, England

Q69:
A lot of the times, the exercises/movements are referred to with more general terms which can be more useful for the day-to-day vernacular. For example, if they bring up they're work out in conversation with the general public, people are more likely to say something like "today is my deadlift day", rather than "today is my beltless, pause at the bottom, glassfloor Conventional Deadlift day" since the former is less of a mouthful and those inexperienced with training wouldn't understand what a lot of that was in the first place. But I do often notice tge more generalised terms like that to be used by people on the more experienced side as they're more familiar with training and tge various terms. But I do think people in my field (personal trainers) who teach people who are unfamiliar with the gym setting should stick to the technical terms for the exercises so the clientor trainee can hopefully better understand what their body is about to perform. And by technical terms, I do not mean the Joel Seedman sort of mumbo-jumbo  like calling a dumbbell chest flye something like a Horizontally Lying Transverse Adduction of Weighted Objects or something. Use the technical terms, but also make sure they understand it.

Also, I don't need to know the names of exercises performed on Vitruvian Cable Machines. Their absolutely obnoxious plastering and spamming of ads everywhere I see has made me decide that these people do not deserve my money.

Q69:
I disagree with the grandfathered traditional term "Resistance Training".

While it originally was coined to refer to using an "External Resistance" to the Concentric Action of an Exercise, it DOES NOT define the FORCE during the Eccentric Action, where the External Force IS NOT, by definition, a "Resistive Force".

I would also assume this goes along with early deference to the Concentric Action, which is also seen in the term "Lifting Weights" neglecting the Eccentric Lowering Weights.

I FAR prefer the terms Force, or Load Training which is inclusive of all forces applied by the body and to the body.

1- State the position of the individual during the exercise (ie, standing, seated, prone (unless otherwise obvious) )

It‚Äôs really clear that people name exercises differently when using an app to record workouts. The Gymshark app for example had a huge library of exercises, but because everyone names exercises differently, my name for an exercise may not be in there but the exercise is in there under a different name. If you can‚Äôt find the exercise you want you can make a new one, but you don‚Äôt benefit from the video library on how to do the lifts. 

Secondarily, learning new moves can be made more difficult by having naming conventions that are non-explanatory. Lifts named after people are a particular quandary. With the internet it‚Äôs easy to find a video of a Pendlay row or a Jefferson deadlift, but the name doesn‚Äôt help you understand what you are doing the way that dumbbell lateral raise or high bar back squat do.

Q69: I think muscle first. If a muscle is ready for a dose of high tension, it's time to apply it. I try to keep the same movement in for 8-20 sessions or so to keep the neural inefficiency minimized, but if the gym is busy it's not the end of the world to do use a barbell instead of dumbbells, for example. And the name of the movement, to me at least, is irrelevant. But that only really counts for those with principled understanding of weight training. If someone doesn't know why they're doing what, they might need clear instruction with clear nomenclature, especially from the start. I also understand a lot of people have decision anxiety issues; even when prescribing their own programming they need clear instruction with familiar movement labels etc. It's "important" for some; and if it's enough to keep those people from giving up on the weight training game, so be it.

Q69: Lifters and coaches have different reasons for calling an exercise a certain way. Some such reasons are habit or tradition within their social circle. Let‚Äôs take for example ‚Äúlying dumbbell triceps extensions.‚Äù Some (like me) call them interchangeably LTEs or ‚Äúskull crushers,‚Äù and specify the resistance implement that is being used (dumbbells, EZ bar, barbell‚Ä¶) if needed. Others, by contrast, prefer to reserve the name ‚Äúskull crushers‚Äù for the version that uses a small barbell or EZ bar. Others yet use ‚Äúskull crushers‚Äù for ROM to the forehead and LTEs for greater ROM resembling that of pull-overs. Whenever there is a potential for ambiguity, however, that is usually prevented or overcome by adding some additional information, such as specifying the lifting implement used. As a result, I don‚Äôt believe the non-univocal naming of exercises results in much ambiguity or confusion in practice. Moreover, I have no idea how a standardized nomenclature could possibly be enforced‚Ä¶

Q69:
My background in a academia is Clinical Exercise Science & Clinical Rehab/ MSK Rehab. The terminologies I use vary depending on who I am talking to:

Gym population: standardised exercise names as this populations tends to recognise these names and/or knows how to vary the exercise depending on how you name it (e.g. wide grip Pulldown vs. Underhand grip vs. Neutral grip)

Physios: name either in reference to what joint is moving (elbow flexion, knee extension etc.) and for multi joint exercises name the direction of motion and name of motion (e.g. vertical pull, horizontal push etc.). Some standardised names used (e.g. squat, but with some flair to previous statement: wide stance squat with external rotation, NOT sumo squat).

Honestly, I think a mixture of both is needed in some way. At a quick glance, I can‚Äôt think of how but I‚Äôm sure if I/ you thought about it a way could be found. Using gym bro terminology helps one recognise there is a difference in how you approach the same exercise, for example, gym goers who are also exercise scientists/ therapists would recognise the benefits and differences between the various Pulldown methods and appreciate them more. But in my experience in rehab work with clinical populations this wouldn‚Äôt be appreciated so much (perhaps maybe because it was clinical population). But at the same time, using the therapists means of naming the exercise allows one to better understand what is being done, why and where it is targeting. Both have their pros and cons and as an academic, it pains me to say, potentially the gym bri way comes out on top.

Let‚Äôs finally get it made into the best way possible!

Q69:
Exercise naming is highly important for research and intervention studies, as everyone reading and possibly replicating the study must be performing the exact same exercise.

However, for general population or clinical practice, the most important exercise name is the one the individual client understands and remembers. Some clients may benefit from the correct name and detailed explanation, where as others may only understand a very basic name or descriptor.

Q69:
I think exercise names change based upon purpose of training and who's doing it.
A baseball player or personal trainer might call a squat a "barbell back squat", while a powerlifter has a multitude of various back squats they might perform and as such have specific names for each of them. As long as there's clear communication from coach to athlete on what's expected and what the purpose is, it's probably not super important what the exercise is called. Although, I do think keeping names consistent for one coach can be important for ease of reference and learning.

Most are a series of kinematic guidelines, vectors, equipment and active muscle groups intended to provide concise context to a particular intended movement. Q69: I think it is important to include as much information as possible in the name. I work with high school athletes, so I try to be clear yet concise and stick to a given format. So I typically try to use position (if different from standard), implement, then movement (incline DB bench press, heels elevated goblet squat). I find that sometimes confusion stems from exercises that do not include the movement in the name, like Romanian deadlift, which is essentially a hinge pattern. I still use the common name, like RDL, as that is likely what others will refer to it as should they go on to the next level. But when possible, I will opt for a name with descriptors in it (so rear-foot elevated split squat instead of Bulgarian split squat, which they will  likely have no clue what that is and will be harder to remember). I harp on the name and try to educate on these as much as possible, like explaining the difference between a split squat (stationary) and a lunge (stepping out and back). I want to teach proper exercise names, as I believe there are proper names for exercises that should help athletes/clients understand what the movement should be. So, I think this is a great survey and am looking forward to the results and hopefully subsequent work that gives a systematic method for exercise names.

Common language between practitioners still remains, in my opinion, one of the biggest barriers. This is amplified if working with general or clinical population who may go from seeing a consultant to physiotherapist to an strength and conditioning coach / athletic trainer; especially if not part of a single MDT.

I do think that standardised exercise names would help, along with definitions such as 'resistance training' being used as opposed to the popular and general 'strength' training title.

Final point...I recall when lateral pulls behind the head was deemed acceptable. Proper technique appears to change over time so assigning a standardised name to a particular movement may prove tricky.
